f alienation, loss, dislocation, and disability; as well as justice, heroism, courage, resilience, generosity, and forgiveness. In addressing these themes, the poems also raise questions about art, politics, citizenship, and moral responsibility. The anthology brings together some of the most compelling poetic voices from different regions of Ukraine. Young and old, female and male, somber and ironic, tragic and playful, filled with extraordinary terror and ordinary human delights, the voices recreate the human sounds of war in its tragic complexity.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aAnti-war poetry, UkrainianvTranslations into English. 0aUkraine Conflict, 2014-vPoetry 0aWar and literaturezUkraine. 0aWar poetry, UkrainianvTranslations into English. 7aPOETRY / Anthologies (multiple authors).2bisacsh  aALEKSANDR KABANOV.  aANASTASIA AFANASIEVA.  aBORIS KHERSONSKY.  aBORYS HUMENYUK.  aDonbass.  aHALYNA KRUK.  aIlya Kaminsky.  aKATERYNA KALYTKO.  aLYUBA YAKIMCHUK.  aLYUDMYLA KHERSONSKA.  aMARIANNA KIYANOVSKA.  aMARJANA SAVKA.  aOKSANA LUTSYSHYNA.  aOSTAP SLYVYNSKY.  aRussia.  aSERHIY ZHADAN.  aUkraine.  aVASYL HOLOBORODKO.  aVASYL MAKHNO.  aYURI IZDRYK.  aabsurdism.  aanthology.  aart.  acollection.  acontemporary.  ahuman rights.  aimagery.  airony.  amodern literature.  apoems.  apoetry.  apolitics.  apost-Soviet.  apostmodernism.  atragedy.  atranslation.  awar.1 aKaminsky, Ilya, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMaksymchuk, Oksana, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMaksymchuk, Oksana, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aRosochinsky, Max, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRosochinsky, Max, eeditor.4edt4http